import statsmodels.api as sm

# Define the dependent variable
y = data['SEP']

# Define the independent variables
X = data[['TAY', 'TAY%', 'REC', 'TAR', 'CTCH%', 'YDS', 'TD', 'YAC/R', 'xYAC/R', '+/-']]

# Add a constant term to the independent variables
X = sm.add_constant(X)

# Fit the linear regression model
model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()

# Print the regression results
print(model.summary())

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# define the independent and dependent variables
x_var = 'SEP'
y_vars = ['TAY', 'TAY%', 'REC', 'TAR', 'CTCH%', 'YDS', 'TD', 'YAC/R', 'xYAC/R', '+/-']

# create subplots for each dependent variable
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=5, figsize=(20, 10))
axes = axes.ravel()

# loop through each dependent variable and create a scatter plot
for i, y_var in enumerate(y_vars):
    # set the dot color based on the slope of the regression line
    slope, intercept = np.polyfit(df[y_var], df[x_var], 1)
    if slope < 0:
        dot_color = 'red'
    else:
        dot_color = 'green'
    axes[i].scatter(df[y_var], df[x_var], alpha=0.5, color=dot_color)
    axes[i].set_xlabel(y_var)
    axes[i].set_ylabel(x_var)
    axes[i].set_title(y_var)

# add a legend to explain the colors
red_patch = plt.plot([],[], marker='o', color='red', linestyle='', markersize=10, label='Negative Slope')
green_patch = plt.plot([],[], marker='o', color='green', linestyle='', markersize=10, label='Positive Slope')
plt.legend(handles=[red_patch[0], green_patch[0]])

# adjust spacing between subplots and display the plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

WHY USE ALL: I am proceeding with the 68 players who met all requirements met because I am looking for Separation's relation to success. Therefore, I want to look at the recievers who have excelled more than most in every category. For this method, we consider that "success" in the NFL includes being above average in all four of our significantly related statistics: Separation, Catch Percentage, Receiving Yards, and Targets. aspect that is valuable to my analysis. we can assume that these players are successful.

To remind, my Model says that recievers with more Separation get less yards on average, but get thrown to more often and have a higher probability of catching the ball. My results from removing the player duplicates state that over a third of the "successfull" players in this dataset prove that my Model's assumptions are indeed true.

Cluster Analysis¶

In [99]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define variables of interest
X = data[['SEP','CTCH%','TAR']]

# Standardize variables
X = (X - X.mean()) / X.std()

# Determine optimal number of clusters using elbow method
wcss = []
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, init='k-means++', random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)
plt.plot(range(1, 11), wcss)
plt.title('Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.show()

# Fit k-means clustering model
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, init='k-means++', random_state=42)
kmeans.fit(X)

# Add cluster labels to data
data['Cluster'] = kmeans.labels_

# Visualize clusters
plt.scatter(X.iloc[:, 0], X.iloc[:, 1], c=kmeans.labels_, cmap='rainbow')
plt.title('Cluster Analysis')
plt.xlabel('SEP')
plt.ylabel('CTCH%')
plt.show()

# Analyze cluster characteristics
cluster_means = data.groupby('Cluster')[['SEP', 'CTCH%', 'TAR']].mean()
print(cluster_means)
